SIMPLE: untie
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Untie
<hw>Un*tie"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>unt⟦ymac⟧gan</ets>. See 1st <er>Un-</er>, and <er>Tie</er>, <pos>v.
t.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To loosen, as something interlaced or knotted; to
disengage the parts of; <as>as, to <ex>untie</ex> a knot</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sacharissa's captive fain⟦br⟧
Would <qex>untie</qex> his iron chain.</q>
<rj><qau>Waller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Her snakes <qex>untied</qex>, sulphurous waters drink.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To free from fastening or from restraint; to let
loose; to unbind.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Though you <qex>untie</qex> the winds, and let them fight⟦br⟧
Against the churches.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All the evils of an <qex>untied</qex> tongue we put upon the
accounts of drunkenness.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To resolve; to unfold; to clear.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They quicken sloth, perplexities <qex>untie</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Denham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Untie</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Untie
<hw>Un*tie"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To become untied or
loosed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Untighten</ent>⟦br⟧
